### Quantitative Trading Strategy Backtesting

Project Scope

- Goal: Build & backtest 2–3 basic trading strategies on equities/FX.
- Deliverables: Python backtester + performance metrics + small dashboard/report.
- Highlight for CV: “Built and backtested trading strategies in Python, evaluated risk-adjusted returns using Sharpe Ratio, Max Drawdown, and Value-at-Risk.”

Tools & Libraries

- Core Language: Python
- Libraries:

    - pandas (data manipulation)
    - numpy (math ops)
    - matplotlib / seaborn / plotly (visualizations)
    - yfinance (free data import)
    - backtrader or zipline (optional backtesting frameworks — you can also code from scratch)
    - arch (for volatility modeling, if you extend later)

- Excel/VBA Add-on:

    - Use Excel for reporting dashboards (PnL curves, summary stats).
    - Use VBA to automate tasks like “import latest backtest results and refresh charts.”
    - This way, you can say: “Integrated Python backtesting pipeline with Excel dashboards via VBA automation for trader-friendly reporting.”

Project Workflow

Data Collection - Done

    Pull historical daily/5-min prices (e.g., AAPL, SPY, EUR/USD).
    Clean missing data.

Feature engineering (before strategy implementation)- Done

    The feature engineering is what is required for developing trading strategies.
    Over here I will create useful indicators and features that will help strategy make buy/sell decisions.
    Essentially done after the pulled data from the source is cleaned and saved to csv(above step - Data Collection).

Strategy Implementation (Examples) - Done

    Moving Average Crossover (e.g., 50/200 SMA).
    Momentum Strategy (buy winners, short losers over lookback window).
    Mean Reversion (Bollinger bands or RSI thresholds) done both

Backtesting Logic - Done

    Track portfolio PnL, cash, positions.
    Include transaction costs (important for realism).

Performance Evaluation - Ongoing

    Metrics: Sharpe Ratio, Sorting Ratio, Max Drawdown, CAGR.
    Risk: Value-at-Risk (VaR), volatility of returns.

Visualization & Reporting

    Equity curve (portfolio value over time).
    Drawdown plot.
    Performance table.

(Optional) Excel/VBA Integration

    Export Python results (PnL, metrics) to CSV.
    Use VBA macro to auto-update charts/summary when new file is dropped.
    Traders love Excel → you’ll show adaptability.

    







